{"/service/ndnp/fu/batch_fu_hastings_ver02/data/sn95047334/00529042358/1930042401/0124.xml":{"full_text":"Page 4\nGADSDEN COUNTY TIMES\n_*, _\nPublished at 112 E. Washington Street, Quincy. Florida\nR. L. SWEGER, Publisher\nEntered at the Postoffice in Quincy, Fla., as second class mail matter\nSUBSCRIPTION PRICE ONE YEAR $2.00. SIX MONTHS, $1.25\nQUINCY, FLORIDA, THURSDAY, APRIL 24. 1930\nProsperity.\nMuch is being said about a general\nreturn of prosperity. Speaking for\ngeneral conditions of ouY nation, the\nemployment situation is improving,\nwhich means that the production of\nwealth\u2014an absolute necessity if we\nare to have prosperity\u2014is increasing.\nV \u2019\u2014g? indm+rislist\nhas advi.'.iced the suggestion that in\ndustry be decentralized, and that the\ncity dweller become a suburban or\ncountry dweller, living on a plot of\nground large enough to be used for\ngrowing some crops for home use or\nfor market.\nMore than once have we heard a\ncity worker say: \u201cI\u2019m going to get\na small place in the country where I\nean raise something to eat. A man\ncan't work all the time, and if you\nlive in the city,, your wages are all\nyou have to live on. But cn a few\nacres in the country, you can grow\nenough food, and then if you miss a\nday's work in the week, or if you\nmiss more than a day\u2019s work during\nthe week, it doesn\u2019t hurt so bad.\u201d\nSome workers in town have adopt\ned this plan, and have enjoyed \u201cbetter\ntimes.\u201d\nLife is undoubtedly better in the\nscburban or country home, if the\nhome has certa'in city conveniences as\nwell as the natural conveniences of\nthe country.\nSuch n is possible in\nthis age of inyeMion For example,\nthe country ho%e can be electrically\nlighted, with electric refrigeration,\nwith home gas plant for cooking\u2014a\ngreater convenience than some homes\nin cities the size of Quincy have.\nThese conveniences cost money, but\nmost of them are sold on the small\ndtwn payment basis, so that the sal\naried man or wage earner may grad\nnmaQy acquire for his very own a\n*4ofcntry home with considerable con\nri'l^bfeneer, rind with automobile trans\n.portation, ehjoy measure of inde\npandence and prosperity greater than\n3irws efforts as a wage or silary\ntranter atone. _\ntffishnethod'\u2019of dMMaddbuHding^i^ -\u00a7e\u00bbn\nin the increasing nuhiber-oft persons\nwho work in town, but'live on a* few\npcres pearby, as there is hardly a\ntown or cfty above the 3,000 popula\ntion mark that has not examples of\nthis kind of householder.\nWhile this plan is attractive to\nthe war r or salary earner of limited,\nmeans, the countr^hdT&^dea atos 1\n\"has considerable atfractTcn^fdY^We\nperson of means. Many successful\nmen ha v? considered their career at a\nparticularly ^satisfying point when\nthey have acquired a country estate.\n(A country estate /for. the man of\nmeans is unlike the country estate of\nthe man who acquires such a place\nbecause it will enable him to prosper\nmove; .but the satisfaction in cne is as\ngreat as the other, and both owners\ndisplay a shrewdness that inspires\nadmiration.\nGreater prosperity is undoubtedly\non the way, for practically all the\npeople; but we believe that greater 1\nend more'stable prosperity is in store\nfor those who are making their plans\nto live-better and toss expensively by 1\nadopting the suggestions of some of\nthe large, manufacturers, particularly\nHenry Ford, and getting out of the\ncongested districts. After all, one\u2019s\nown vine and fig tree contains allur\ning- possibilities.\n-o\u2014 I\nWe Are On Eaay Street.\nCompared with the rest of the\nworld, the United States is on Easy 1\nStreet. The thought is suggested by\nthe n ri cf the British Govern-\nment to increase the income tax over\nthere to 2214 percent. Americans\nwho grumble st a tax on incomes\nwhich begins at one-half of one per\ncent and does not go above two per\ncent until your income is more than'\n$lO,OOO a year, certainly ought to\nfeel that they are on Easy Street by\ncomparison with the English.\nTo be sure, we have taxes which\nthey do not have in England, such as\nthe tax on real estate improvements,\nbut on the whole we carry a lighter'\nburden of taxation than any other]\nnation.\nA recent report of the condition of\nth< workers in Continental Europe\nrepeals the fact, amazing and almost\nshocking to us but a commonplace\nover there, that the vast majority of\nwage-earners in France. Germany and]\nsome other parts of Europe nev^r\nearn enough to buy new clothes for\ntheir families and themselves. Whole\ncommunities dress from infancy to\nold age in second-hand clothes, made\nfor and worn originally by persons of\nthe \u201cupper classes.\u201d The second\nhand clothing business in America is\nalmost extinct. Even in the poorest\ndistricts cf the largest cities the\n\u201cok- clothes emporiums\u2019 which used\nto flourish are now largely given\nover to the gathering of old clothes\nfor export to markets where the peo\nple are too poor to buy new clothes,\nwhile the sons and daughters of the\nold people, who were brought up to\nspend no money for new clothes^\ndress in the latest fashion.\nThis is not a condition brought\nabr.ut by the war. It existed long be\nfore the war\u2014has always existed so\nfar as Europe goes. It is easy to\nunderstand wi h what hopefulness\nEuropean workers look forward to the\nJ introduction of American industrial\nJ methods, which are based on making\nthe workers into consumers by giving\nthem high enough wages so they can\nI afford to buy new shoes. They still\nI do not believe the stories they hear\nj from this side about American wage\n1 workers owning automobiles and\nradios.\nIt is easy to understand why, with\nthe great mass of people unable to\nJ purchase even the necessities of life,\nas we understand them, European in\nj d -stry lags behind our own. With\nmarkets limited to the small percent\nage of the wealthy and the exg^t\ntrade how can it be otherwise?\no\nMoving Toward Permanent Peace.\nNo mere battleships will be built\nby the United States, Great Britain,\nFrance, Italy or Japan before 1936.\nThose nations had agreed in 1921 on\na ten-year \u201cbattleship holiday.\u201d By\nmutual agreement they have extend\ned the holiday for another five years.\nThree of those five powers have\nagreed to dispose of certain specified\nfighting ships new' in commission,\nthus reducing their navies below their\npresent strength. France and Italy\nhave not yet come into that agree\nment, as they have some mutual dif\n^erenees in regard to the Mediter\ni n to adjust, but there is lit\n\u00fcb* that eventually both of\ntl esc nations will join the other great\nsea powers in sinking warships.\nNaval reduction is a long step tow\nard permanent world peace. Com\nplete disarmament is, in the present\nstage of civilization, impracticable,\nbut an overmastering navy -would not\nmake for peace, either, Oikr-.purpoSe\nwould be suspected by all the;. rgst of\nthe world if we continued to maintain\na naval force out of proportion to\nour coast-line and our interests on\nthe sea.\n\u201cCertainly the way of peace lies\nneither in the rattling of the scabbard\nj nor in the absurd\u00ae \u00bbjm ent,, of defense,\u201d\nHewer,, axjd he added,\nteri/ he alright be- accused of \"pacif\nisan,\u201d whatever that is, \u201cLet no one\nmistake me; there is a price no na\ntion can afford to pay for peace.\u201d\n-0\u2014\n\n\nSecretary Gray\n\nMiami Herald: The resignation of\nWilliem M. Igou as Secretary of State\nand the appointment of R. A. Gray,\nAssistant Comptroller, to fill the va\nj cancy, has not been unexpected in\ncapital circles.\nThe failing health of the former\nsecretary has made it alniostK. jm\npnssible for him to undergo the rigors\nof a cempaign for office iij the com\ning primary. Igou was opposed by\nthree active campaigners, and there\nmay be at least one other qualify. A\nweak heart and a strong race are not\ncompatible.\nAssistant Comptroller Gray, with\nlong years of faithful service to the\nstate, and with the office of State\nCommander of the American Legion\njust behind him, was the one logical\nman to step in behind the faltering\nsteps of Igou.\nGray is not apt to be as friendly\nto the administration as was Igou,\nbut he will be better than any of\nthose now campaigning for the office.\nGray is good enough politician not to\nbe a thorn in the flesh to any gover\nnor, unless that governor is so far\ngone down the scale of popularity\nthat open hostility would be un\nquestionably policy. The new secre\ntary will go into his important place\non the various boards with the back\nground of many yeais of harmonious\nw'ork with his associates of the cabi^\nnet, and with an understanding\nstate business gained from Tons mto*\nministration of the State Banking\nDepartment, which comes under the\ncomptroller.\nThis change, in time for Gray to\nqualify and run, to the governor\u2019s best\nbet. Igou would have been better for\nhis purpose. Gray probably will not\nI play up to the administration leads\nwith that satisfactory whole-hearted\nness that characterized Igou\u2019s work,\nbut Gray will be a better man on\nthose boards from the viewpoint of\nthe people.'\nWell Used Still Is\nFound By Officers\nA liquor manufacturing outfit\nshowing evidences of having rendered\nconsiderable service was destroyed by\nDeputies T. R. Nazworth and R. W.\nLong Tuesday morning, about three\nmiles this side of Havana, on\nThomas mill creek. Beer containers\nwith 107 gallons of mash, getting\nready for distilling, were also de\nstroyed. The still was a copper bot\ntom apparatus, with a capacity of\nabout 40 gallons. No arrests have\nbeen made in connection with the cap\nture.\n\u201cCan a Christian be a Com\nmunist?\u201d is asked. Maybe so, but]\nin Russia a Communist had\u2019rather\nrough sledding if he tries to work at\nbeing a Christian.\nTroop 202 Entertains\nParent-Son Banquet\nScout Trocp 202 entertained with\none of the most enjoyable affairs of\nthe season last Thursday evening,\nApril 17, when the annual parent\nson secut banquet was held at the\nKenwood Coffee House.\nAbout one hundred guests wete\npresent, including Trcop 202, their\nparents and a few invited guests;\nalgo Mr. Douglas Burnett, of Talla\nhassee, the new Suwannee River\nCouncil executive, and Mrs. Burnett.\nScoutmaster N. F. Fain presided,\nand an enjoyable program was car\nried cut. A few stunts by the boys,\na mock band, calculated to make\nSousa turn gieen with envy were aril\nenjoyed. A round table discussion cf\nparents, views on whether scouting is\nj worthwhile or not, was invited and\nmet with many glovring responses by\n1 1 enthusiastic parents.\nIt was proposed to build a screened,\nnicely put up \u201cshack\u201d on the river,\nfor the boys to sleep in, on their\n1 camps. Generous-hearted \u201cdads\u201d im\n\u201cmediately; lesponded with enough\nbowls roses,. ;anapdragons .and\nlarkspur, and the; tWo-course dinner\nwas delicious. Alt 5 the ;boysf v and\ntheir parents report a dpliihtful\ntime.\u2014Reporter.\n]May 2 Date Set For\nThomasville Rose Show\nI May 2 has been officially named\nas the date for the Ninth Annual\nRose Show to be held in Thomasville.\nThis date was selected after due con\nsideraticn of the weather conditions\nthat have existed in the past few\nweeks and the apparent progress of\nrose growth.\nThe show will be held in thg to\nbacco warehouse, \\which is large\nenough for a great variety of dis-\nplays of all types. The space fop pri\nj vate and plantation exhibits for the\ncurrent show has practically all been\ntaken and indications point to a\nmost interesting display of a great\nhr variety of roses as well as other\n'flowers.\ni Two band concerts will be given\nduring the day, afternoon and even\ni ing. Traffic will be carefully handled\nand ample parking space will be pro-\nvided. Special arrangements r have\nI been made for supplying food to\nthose who will visit the city. The\nshow will open at 11 a. m., and will\nclose at 10 p. m. The show will be\nopen only one day. Visitors will all\nreceive a* most cordial welcome.\nThere is no admission charge.\nTO- 1? if'\nBeautiful Easter Program\nof Music Baptist Church\nSunday evening, under the direc-J\ntion of Mrs. A. D. Mayo, choir direc\ntor, and with Mrs. Robert Armstrong;\nas organist, the members of the choir\nof the Baptist church qffered to the\npublic a beautiful program cf Easter\nmusic.\nThe choir sang \u201cLow in the Grave\nHe Lay\u201d in the distance, and after\ntwo verses of this song, the choir in\nsurplices, took its place within the\nchancel and finished the song. D. A. i\nAvant read the devotional for the ser-\nvice, after which the following pro- i\ngram of music was given:\nThe Lord Reigneth\u2014Choir.\nMan of Sorrows-\u2014Mrs. G. E. Bor\ning and choir.\nGethsemane Men\u2019s two part\nf iT\n.A [ygU Putmm Cnmmw\nI-. Sgt V Tbabe\nMal L EkS\nV? nfl\u00df t* Sus Purina Cf HMM\nt a MK sp^y\nwIL\u00ae!\nP\u00abHM r w j\nmilr ill ll\n11 iu\nLinl^Tcur ^loHPlan\nTogether With Puritan D out ton Cretonnes\nDon\u2019t stop with cretonne draperies\u2019 The\nsame notes of color repeated in slip covers,\nscreen-., vanity flounces, pillows, etc.,enhance\nthe interest of your draperies.\nPicture a bedroom for instance, with the\ndainty rose, green and gold Puritan Doulton\nCretonne \u201cSpray\u201d at the windows. Beneath\nthe t\u00bbroup of windows is a dainty dressing\ntable flounced with \u201cSpray.\u201d The bed is\npainted green with a delicate rose and go! J\ntnm and \u201cSpray\u201d is used for the spread. A\nchair is upholstered in plain rose rep. s\nPurtcaq Doulton Crctpnnes^\nAre Guaranteed Sunlast and WaCtiIBU L.\nThe guarantee is printed on the selvage of 3\newery yard. Stop in and see our exhibit of\nthese dunning fast color cretonnes.\nP. W. Wilson Company\n\nTallahassee, Florida\nGADSDEN COUNTY TIMES\nj An exchange denies the story\n1 about a souvenir hunter picking up\nt a. half-smoked cigar thrown away by\nMr. Coolidge. It Says the former\npresident is not that wasteful.\nf\nMrs^M. I. (finnan\nr X. J\nWti\n1 //V\n1 rfi\nJ hQ\\ 4:\no\nr g\nM l\\ t\nI\nSpring Fashions\nH\nr g AreUnusuallyinteresting\nThis Season.\nThe new ferhtmnc details af\n!;g ford such delightful possibiL\ng ities to the leading stylists,\n\u2018ig whose creeds a<e to faithfully\nadhered to by true ^oilowais\ni f jof fashion.\ntlg \u2019Z e\ntp See our outstaadr'v CoHec\nft\ng non of Street ana Afternron\nFrocks Defe-sed by..\nI\n\u00bbjg .-\u2019.-I-\ng (Exclusive with thiistoie).\n\u25a0ig j.\n8 L. Massey\ng Mae\u2019s Shop\nI Tallahassee\nA.?;\u2019'\u2019' \u00abi-\ni chorus.\nCalvary\u2014Mr. Blucher Blair and\nchoir. t\nA Whisper of Hope\u2014Mesdames A. j\nD. Mayo and Ray Lester.\nDawns the x'lew Day\u2014Women\u2019s\nchorus, men\u2019s chcius and choir.\nHail to the King\u2014Mrs. Walker\nBbir and choin\nThe Morning is Breaking\u2014Mes\ndames Walker Blair and R. F. God\nard. j\nThe King Crimes Forth\u2014Choir.\nHasanna\u2014Jules Grimier\u2014Mrs. A.\ni D. Mayo.\nThe King of Glory\u2014Choir.\nYe Shall Live Also\u2014G. H. Boring\nand choir.\nThe Resurrection and the Life\u2014\nChoir.\nWant Ads\nFOR RENT\u2014Completely furnished\napar.ment, strictly private. Phone\n172._ 3-6-tf\nFOR SALE\u2014Used plumbing fix\ntr.res* See Rocco, the Plumber.\n4-24-tf\n\u2014\u2014_\nFOR RENT\u2014Two five-room houses\n\u2018in Germantown. H. Feinberg.\n_4-24-2 t\nFOR SALE\u2014Electric air compres-\nsor. Varnadore\u2019s Filling Station.\n4-3-tf\nFOR RENT\u2014Nine-room house <>n\nW. Jefferson street, in good repair.\nI Annly J. J. Gatlin, city. 4-24-2 t\nFOR SALE\u2014Medel T Ford truck,\ncab and good body, first class condi\ntion. Varr.adores Filling Station.\n4-3-tf/\nFOR SALE Pulverized tobacco\nstems; good for poultrymen, lawns,\ngardens, etc. D. L. McPherson, city.\nlt*\nFOR SALE QR R\u00a3NT\u2014Six-room\nresidence on N. JacksoiY Sts* formerly\nOCcup\u00df'd by Mrsr Hattie Munroe. See\n\u2022Or phoife\u2019' 4-24-tf\nFOR SALE\u2014At a bargain. White\nRisosie# kitchen cabinet, originally\ncost S7S.-' In perfect condition. Mrs.\nS. B. Rouse. 4-24-tf\nFOR SALE\u2014Early matchless to\nmato plants a'nd Giant bell pepper\nnlants, ready to. set. Any quantity.\nMcKeown, the florist. Telephone 99.\n4-24-tf\nSTOVE WOOD. FIRE WOOD\u2014\nCall 425. Prompt service. 1 1-2 ton\ntruck load, $3 50. Any length, to\nist stove or fireplace. Pine and\nhardwoods. W. R. Moore and Ar\nthur Cooper. 4-17-tf\nFOR SALE \u2014Large Chicago manu\nfacturer has a piano near Quincy\nwhich is slightly used and partly paid\nfor. We will sell this to a responsi\nble party willing to complete small\nmonthly payments. For full particu\nlars address P. O. Box 172, Chicago,\nIllinois. 4-24-3 t\nFOR SALE\u2014I am offering at bar\ngain prices one Edison phonograph\nand 75 records, in good conditio^;\none gcod leather saddle; a 12 gaug$\nshot gun and a telephone. Wjll con-\u2019\nsider trading for other articles. C.\nT. King, Rfd. 1, Box 43-A, Faceville,\nGa. Residence one mile south of;\nSylvania church on Quincy and\nHutchinson ferry rpad... It\nApril 26 Clean-Up Pay\nat Mt. Pleasant Cemetery\nApril 26 is cleaning day at Old Mt.\nPleasant cemetery. Come and help\ngive tl(e entire cemetery a thorough\ndean ing l Anyone who has loved ones\nresting here and who can not come\nand work please send a donation to\nMrs. A. H. Davis sc help can be hired.\nThere is a lot of work and it will take\na large crowd. Bring lunch so you\ncan work all day.\u2014Mrs. A. H. Da\u2019vis.\nTo the Voters of The\nThird Congressional\nDistrict:\nI am a candidate in\nthe Democratic primary\nin June to succeed my\nself as your representa\ntive in Washington. I\nhave endeavored to\ngive you individual and\ncollective service, for\nthe little more than\nthree years that I have\nbeen employed by my\npeople here. On account\nof contacts and associa\ntions cultivated in this\ntime, I know better how\nto serve you more effec\ntively than ever before.\nHave no other occupa\ntion; or profession than\nto look after your busi\nness.\nHave never neglected\nto respond to requests\nmade of me, whether by\nthose that voted for me\nor against me. Have\ntried to be a representa\ntive for all the people,\nall the time, not only in\nthe halls of congress,\nbut before the numer\nous departments,\nboards and bureaus.\nI appreciate more\nthan I can express the\ntrust imposed in me in\nthe past. I promise my\ncontinued devotion to\nyour welfare. \u201cKeep\nTom Yon on the job\u201d as\nyour congressman.\nSincerely,\nTOM A. YON,\nCongressman Thi r d\nFlorida District.\nTenter prise Theatre\nINTERSTATE ENTERPRISES DIRECTION\nTHE CREAM OF THE SCREEN WHILE IT*S NEW\nE. T. HARDEN. Manager NAT WILLIAMS, Managing Director\nWEEK BEGINNING APRIL 28, 1930\nYour name printed on this side of program entitles ycu to free admis\nsion to \u201cDANGEROUS PARADISE,\u201d with NANCY CARROLL and RICH\nARD ARLEN.\nMONDAY\u2014\u201cTHE BISHOP MURDER CASE,\u201d with BASIL RATH\nBONE, LEILA HYAMS, ROLAND YOUNG, GEORGE MARION, NELLIE\nBLY BAKER. From the pen of S. S. Van Dine. We admit thu. the talk\ning screen has brought an orgy of mystery pictures, and we\u2019ve steered clear\nof lots of them lately. But here\u2019s one you shculd see. It tops the list for\nthrills and romance. As you know, Rathbone is about the most finished\nactor on the talking screen, and this is one cf his best toles. (Mr. and Mrs.\nE. L. Elavkbarn, Jamieson, Fla.) Paramount act, \u201cMARCHING TO\nGEORGIA.\u201d PATHE AUDIO REVIEW. 15 and 30c matinee. 15 and 40c\nevening.\nTUESDAY- WEDNESDAY \u201cDANGEROUS PARADISE,\u201d with\nNANCY CARROLL, RICHARD ARLEN, WARNER OLAND. Breathless\nadventure! Tropical romance! \u201cSweetie\u201d is here in her first starring role.\nShe\u2019ll win your heart anew. More bewitching than she was in \u201cDance of\ni Life.\u2019 A woman-hating ma'n and a man-loving woman alone in a South\nSea paradise. Arlen as the tropical lover. Directed by William Wellman,\ndirector of \u201cWINGS.\u201d Teeming with action. Glowing with young ardor.\n(Mr. and Mrs. T. C. Arnold). PATHE NEWS. STAN LAUREL AND\nOLIVER HARDY in \u201cNIGHT OWLS.\u201d Which means sterling in the teugh\n-1 craft. 15 \u00bb\u2019nd 30c matinee. 15 and 40c evening.\nTHURSDAY\u2014\u201cPARIS BOUND.\u201d with ANN HARDING, FREDERIC\ni MARCH. It would ccst you $5.50 to see this pair of stars on Broadway,\ni Here you have them in Philip Barry\u2019s International stage success for panic\nprices. A gripping and timely film. A sophisticated story of the trials\nand tribulations of a wealthy young couple\u2014marriage sacrificed on an altar\nof indifference\u2014love blown to bits by petty jealousies. A daring expose\ncf high society. (Mr. and Mrs. W. L. Trenchard.) VITAPHONE ACT,\n\u201cTHE MUSIC SHOP.\u201d PATHE NEWS. 15 and 30c matinee. 15 and 40c\nevening.\nFRIDAY\u2014\u201cTHE WEDDING RING,\u201d with H. B. WARNER, LOIS\nWILSON, KATHLEEN WILLIAMS. A flapper sister takes a gocd man\naway from her older sister and marries him. And when the latter starts\nfighting back for her man, you have interest and humor. Founded on\nErnest Pascal\u2019s \u201cDark Swan.\u201d (Mr. and Mrs. L. S. Munroe.) You\u2019ve read.\nI or heard of the book, and must realize that its presentation by the abeve\ncast must result in perfect entertainment. \u201cDOING PHIL A FAVOR\u201d is\nthe talking ccmedy. 15 and 30c matinee. 15 and 40c evening.\nSATURDAY\u2014\u201cHUNTING TIGERS IN INDIA,\u201d with a cast of man\n/eating cannibals and wild animals of India\u2019s jungles. You\u2019ll see wild tigers\nattack an elephant and other scenes that will leave you gasping. Nothing\nstaged about it. It\u2019s one cf the most instructive pictures we\u2019ve ever shown,\nas well as most interesting. Every child should see it All adults will thrill\nto it. \u201cACE OF SCOTLAND YARDS.\u201d \u201cTHE BIG JEWEL CASE.\u201d 15\nand 30c all day.\n2 Next Week\u2014Dennis King in \u201cThe Vagabond King.\u201d\nII I I II I\nMeeting of Gadsden\nS. S. Convention Apr. 13\nThe Baptist Sunday School Cokyen-i\ntion of Gadsden county met with the\nGreensbo\u00df4\u00bb church on April 13^ A<\ntotal M\nworkers were pres\u00ab^ Qitr,abU.\npresident, had a well-prepared pro\ngram. which was enjoyed by all pres\nent. The next meeting will be with\nthe Gretnu' church, May 11. at 3 p. m.\nYou are urged to, attend.\u2014Reporter, f\nj 'V \u2014P\nAdvertise in the Times.\nPiggly Wiggly\nThe correctness of the fundamental principal upon\nwhich the PIGGLY WIGGLY system was founded has\nbeen attested by its nation-wide growth, by the millions\nof dollars that it has saved for the consuming public.\nJ R Like the idea of 48 states\u2014each with its own rights\nand own control over its individual territory\u2014but com\nbined under one nation for mutual protection and profit\nFriday-Saturday, April 25-26\nSUGAR 53\u201c\nCOFFFF Maxwell House, QCjc\nWl I\u25a0al a one can Ow\nCOFFFF Luzianne si.is\nM |ji l 3 lb. pai] with china\nPF A f\u2019HFQ Osceola, halves, OOc\nPINF APPI F Libb y\u2019 s sliced 94 c\nA Xa V a l.^l a No. 2 can\nHOMINY 2 25 e\nCORN Bluc Rid e 17 c\nPF AC Blue R idge, 17c\n1 jf o i can, 2 for f\nKIDNEY BEANS 25 c\nPEANUT BUTTER 23 c\npATQIIP B I iqc\nMALTED MILK 48 c\nRICE Ro 25 c\nBUTTER 41 e\nBACON i u 39 e\nTOILET PAPER 13\u2018\nLARD^t\u2018 de 25 c\nFLOURS\u2019 94\u2018\nSOAP^ 1 20 c\nPRUNES 18 c\nLEMONS 24 e\nLETTUCE s dHe d 10^\nApril 24, 1930\nMrs. Leona Faircloth\nHonor Guest Entertainment\nI At\nMr. and Mrs. Ross Harris will en\ntertain Thursday nighthonoring Urs.\nLfona Faircloth, who writs\u2019, eIMtM As-\nAj*, meetinjfc, rwbntly jp ^Putmpa, and\nJBr. Wiia Mr's. Gunn, of South Jackson\nville. Miss Lillian Kilpatrick, Wor\nthy Grand Matron, and Mrs. Lena\nBird, Past Grand Matron, will also\nbe distinguished guests on this oc\ncasion. The cfficirs of Washington\nChapter No. 43 arfe invited to share\nthe hospitalities of Mr. and Mrs. Har\nris at this time.","height":"26163","width":"19827"}}
